#X text 31 59 We can use an oscillator to modulate the pulse width of a square wave. This is "Pulse Width Modulation" - or "PMW" for short. Similarly to Hard Sync \, this greatly alters the timbre and partial strengths and is usually done with Low Frequency. The PWM concept can also apply to [vsaw~] \, which generates sawtooth/triangular waves., f 70;
#X obj 765 419 adsr~ 10 25 0.5 500;
#X text 594 25 Below we also sync the LFOs so they start at the same position on Note-Ons (you may choose not to want this \, of course). For the square wave we have a sine so it starts at the middle position. We also rescale it to the 0.1 to 0.9 range to avoid the more extremes width that are more like impulses. For the [vsaw~] we have a cosine so it starts at the extreme saw like waveform. As an excercize you can add more effects and other things we've seen before like vibrato and stuff., f 65;
#X text 136 579 Next we'll see more proper basic synthesis techniques.;
